# No Sibling Re-exports

Modules must **own** what they export. Do not re-export symbols defined in a sibling module.

## Rules

- **Export** only what this module defines (functions, types, constants authored here).
- **Import** shared symbols from their defining module (or from the package public entry).
- **Do not** `export { x } from "./sibling"` or `import { x } from "./sibling"; export { x }` in utils/components/services.
- **Exception:** package barrels such as `packages/*/src/index.ts` (and similar public API entrypoints) may re-export the package surface.

## Why

Re-exports create multiple “homes” for the same symbol, obscure ownership, and tempt callers to import from the wrong module.

## Examples

```typescript
// BAD — sibling re-export
export { SYSTEM_SECURITY_DEPOSIT_INCOME_TYPE_NAME } from "./property-income-line-type-config";
export { addMonthsToIsoDate } from "./lease-date-utils";

// GOOD — import for local use only; callers import from the defining module
import { isSystemSecurityDepositIncomeLineTypeName } from "./property-income-line-type-config";

export function isDepositIncomeLineType(type: { name: string }): boolean {
  return isSystemSecurityDepositIncomeLineTypeName(type.name);
}

// GOOD — package barrel (packages/shared/src/index.ts)
export { SYSTEM_SECURITY_DEPOSIT_INCOME_TYPE_NAME } from "./property-income-line-type-config";
export { addMonthsToIsoDate } from "./lease-date-utils";
```
